We take \mathscr {C} to be:






        the category of topological spaces and continuous maps, with final object e=P^t;





        the category of pairs (X,F) where X is a topological space and F is an abelian sheaf on X, with an arrow (u,f)\colon (Y,F)\to (X,G) consisting of a continuous map u\colon  Y\to  X and a u-morphism () f\colon  G\to  F, with final object e=(P^t,0).

Let u\colon Y_\bullet \to X_\bullet be a morphism of topological simplicial spaces, with cone C(u). Let F be an abelian sheaf on X_\bullet and G an abelian sheaf on Y_\bullet , and let f\colon G\to F be a u-morphism. The cone C(f) of f is an abelian sheaf on C(u), and we set
2439hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1.xmlEquation6.3.2.1hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2 \operatorname {H}^n(C(u),C(f)) = \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G). \tag{6.3.2.1}
These are the relative cohomology groups. We can easily show that they fit into a long exact sequence
2440hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.2hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.2.xmlEquation6.3.2.2hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2 \ldots \to \operatorname {H}^i(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G) \to \operatorname {H}^i(X_\bullet ,F) \to \operatorname {H}^i(Y_\bullet ,G) \to \ldots . \tag{6.3.2.2}

html:ol.html:li:
Construction (b) above is natural in (G,X,F). We set
2281hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.3hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.3.xmlEquation6.1.2.3hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2 \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F) = \operatorname {H}^\bullet ([X/G]_\bullet ,F^\bullet ) \tag{6.1.2.3}
(mixed cohomology of X,G with coefficients in F). Under the hypotheses of (a), if F is the inverse image of F^{-1} on S=X/G, then
2282hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.4hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2.4.xmlEquation6.1.2.4hodge-theory-iii-6.1.2 \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,G;F) = \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X/G,F^{-1}) \tag{6.1.2.4}
(for a principal homogeneous space). This generalises (which is the case F=\underline {\mathbb {Z}}).

